t_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n<!-- Image with inadequate rationale removed: [[Image:ElectionsNWTLogo.png|right|400px]] -->\nThis is a '''list''' of territorial '''elections''' in '''[[Northwest Territories]]''', Canada since 1870. The Northwest Territories operates on a [[consensus government]] using the [[First Past the Post]] electoral system. The territory does not presently recognize political parties.\n\n==Voting and consensus government==\n{{main|Consensus government|First Past the Post}}\nNorthwest Territories elects members to the [[Legislative Assembly of the Northwest Territories]] under a [[non-partisan]] system known as [[consensus government]]. The election only decides who represents each district. The newly elected members of the assembly convene after the election to vote amongst themselves to decide which members become part of the [[Executive Council (Commonwealth countries)|Executive Council]].<ref name=\"consensusref\">[http://archives.cbc.ca/IDC-1-73-1021-5781/politics_economy/elections_nwt/clip1 Making sense of consensus government CBC Radio clip October 22, 1985] accessed April 13, 2006</ref>\nThis system of government has evolved in the Northwest Territories since 1870.\n\nThe voting method to elect members is the [[First Past the Post]] electoral system. Voters under this system pick the top candidate by the number of votes cast regardless of the percent of votes earned by a candidate. With a few historical exceptions all [[Electoral district (Canada)|electoral districts]] in the Northwest Territories are represented by a single member. First Past the Post has been used since the first election in 1881. [[Elections NWT]] is the independent regulatory body in charge of overseeing elections.\n\n==History of elections==\n{{main|History of Northwest Territories|Politics of Northwest Territories}}\n\nThe [[Northwest Territories]] has been through a number of distinct changes in how the territory is governed and how government has been selected.  These changes have coincided with several major boundary changes since the [[Government of Canada]] acquired the territory in 1870.<ref name=\"atlasref\">[http://atlas.gc.ca/site/english/maps/historical/territorialevolution Territorial evolution in Canada] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050929194330/http://atlas.gc.ca/site/english/maps/historical/territorialevolution |date=2005-09-29 }} accessed April 13, 2006</ref> From 1869 to 1876 the Northwest Territories was run by an interim government, first led by lieutenant-governor [[William McDougall (politician)|William McDougall]], and a council appointed by Ottawa. This council was governed under the ''Temporary Government of Rupert's Land Act, 1869'' and the ''Manitoba Act, 1870'' The council itself sat in [[Manitoba]] and was made up of Members of the [[Manitoba Legislative Assembly]].<ref name=\"popref\">[http://www.collectionscanada.ca/confederation/023001-2245-e.html History of Northwest Territories in Confederation] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060211154617/http://www.collectionscanada.ca/confederation/023001-2245-e.html |date=2006-02-11 }} April 13, 2006</ref>\n\nIn 1876 the Temporary Council was dissolved and a new council was appointed under the ''Northwest Territories Act''. Members could be elected to join the council if an area of {{convert|1000|sqmi|km2|-3}} had 1000 inhabitants. The first such electoral districts were created in 1881.<ref name=\"distcreate\">[http://www.ourfutureourpast.ca/law/page.aspx?id=1458809 Electoral Districts created by proclamation Northwest Territories Ordinances 1881] accessed April 13, 2006</ref> According to the Act, when the council reached twenty members, it would gain control of territorial affairs from the crown. The Council achieved this requirement in 1886. The council was renamed to an assembly and was dissolved in 1888. Twelve elections to rotate and elect members to new districts were held during the period between 1876 and 1888.<ref name=\"1888ref\">[http://www.saskarchives.com/web/seld/1-00.pdf Election Results and Dates 1876 - 1905 from Saskatchewan Archives] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928101028/http://www.saskarchives.com/web/seld/1-00.pdf |date=2007-09-28 }} accessed April 13, 2006</ref>\n\nFive general elections would occur between 1888 and 1905, as the territories underwent significant growth. In 1897 after an amendment to the Northwest Territories Act, the territories experienced a short-lived period of partisan politics that led to the [[Northwest Territories Liberal-Conservative Party]]<ref name=\"partyref\">Election Results by party printed in the [[Calgary Herald]] various dates May 1902</ref> being elected in the fourth and fifth elections until 1905. The government in this period was made of members from the populated regions in the south. No members from the Arctic region would sit in government until 1947.<ref name=\"assemref\">[http://www.assembly.gov.nt.ca/visitorinfo/factsheets/history.html History of the Northwest Territories from the Northwest Territories Legislative Assembly] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060714133328/http://www.assembly.gov.nt.ca/visitorinfo/factsheets/history.html |date=2006-07-14 }} accessed April 13, 2006</ref> In 1905, [[Alberta]] and [[Saskatchewan]] were carved out of the Northwest Territories. As a result, the population dropped from approx 160,000 to 17,000, of which 16,000 were aboriginal and had no right to vote under Canadian law.<ref name=\"popref\" /> The government of the Northwest Territories defaulted back to its 1870 constitutional status, and once again came under federal control. This period of the second council, which governed from [[Ottawa]], lasted from 1905 to 1951.\n\nIn 1951, the second council was dissolved in order to return to elections. Rather than being fully elected body, the Councils and Assemblies were a mix of elected and appointed members. After 1975 the Assembly became fully elected. In 1999 the Northwest Territories underwent one last division as the territory of [[Nunavut]] was created out of the eastern half of the territory.\n\nThe boundary changes have resulted in a disconnect in four periods of the territorial government. The records of the temporary council falls under the archives of the Manitoba government, while the archives and electoral records of the period of government from 1876 to 1905 were retained by the Saskatchewan government. The archives of the council from 1905 to 1951 are under the Canadian Government who appointed the council from that period.\n\n<center>\n<gallery>\nImage:Canada Provinces Territories 1870.png|In 1870, NWT covered much of Canada. The government was in the south part of the territory. A number of boundary changes would occur over the next 35 years but have little effect on the government until 1905.\nImage:Canada Provinces Territories 1905.png|The Northwest Territories boundary change in 1905 marked a major shift in the territorial government and demographics of the remaining population.\nImage:Canada Provinces Territories 1949.png|The government evolved again under the 1912 to 1999 boundaries. The issue of splitting the territory in half surfaced in the early 1960s.\nImage:Northwest Territories, Canada.svg|The current Northwest Territories as of 1999 was decided by a series of plebiscites and capped over a decade of consultation, committee work and land claim agreements.\n</gallery>\n</center>\n\n==List of elections==\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#efefef\" |\n!| Date\n!| General elections and<br />[[By-election]]s prior to 1888\n!| [[List of Northwest Territories Legislative Assemblies|Assembly]]\n!colspan=2| # elected\n!| [[List of Northwest Territories premiers|Elected leaders]]\n!| [[History of Northwest Territories capital cities|Capital city]]\n|-\n|colspan=5 align=center|[[Temporary North-West Council]], no elections from 1870 to 1876\n|rowspan=14 align=center|Appointed<br />[[List of Northwest Territories lieutenant-governors|Lieutenant Governor]]\n|[[Fort Garry]]\n|-\n|colspan=5 align=center|[[1st Council of the Northwest Territories]], no elections from 1876 to 1881\n|[[Fort Livingstone, Saskatchewan|Fort Livingstone]]\n|-\n|March 23, 1881\n|[[Lorne (N.W.T. electoral district)|Lorne]] by-election<ref name=\"ref1888\" group=\"Note\">Elections prior to 1888 were held 3 years from the last in each district, or upon creation by the Lieutenant Governor or vacancy.</ref>\n|rowspan=12|[[1st Council of the Northwest Territories|1st Council]]\n|colspan=2 align=center|1\n|rowspan=5|[[Battleford, Saskatchewan|Battleford]]\n|-\n|May 29, 1883\n|[[Edmonton (N.W.T. electoral district)|Edmonton]] by-election\n|colspan=2 align=center|1\n|-\n|June 5, 1883 \n|[[Lorne (N.W.T. electoral district)|Lorne]] by-election\n|colspan=2 align=center|1\n|-\n|August 13, 1883\n|[[Moose Jaw (N.W.T. electoral district)|Moose Jaw]] by-election<br />[[Regina (N.W.T. electoral district)|Regina]] by-election<br />[[Qu'Appelle (N.W.T. electoral district)|Qu'Appelle]] by-election\n|colspan=2 align=center|3\n|-\n|August 31, 1883\n|[[Broadview (N.W.T. electoral district)|Broadview]] by-election\n|colspan=2 align=center|1\n|-\n|June 28, 1884\n|[[Calgary (N.W.T. electoral district)|Calgary]] by-election<br />[[Moose Mountain (N.W.T. electoral district)|Moose Mountain]] by-election\n|colspan=2 align=center|2\n|rowspan=15|[[Regina, Saskatchewan|Regina]]\n|-\n|September 15, 1885 \n|[[1885 Northwest Territories election|1885 election]]\n|colspan=2 align=center|11\n|-\n|October 14, 1886\n|[[Qu'Appelle (N.W.T. electoral district)|Qu'Appelle]] by-election\n|colspan=2 align=center|1\n|-\n|July 8, 1886 \n|[[Moose Mountain (N.W.T. electoral district)|Moose Mountain]] by-election\n|colspan=2 align=center|1\n|-\n|July 14, 1886\n|[[Calgary (N.W.T. electoral district)|Calgary]] by-election\n|colspan=2 align=center|2\n|-\n|May 24, 1887 \n|[[Qu'Appelle (N.W.T. electoral district)|Qu'Appelle]] by-election\n|colspan=2 align=center|2\n|-\n|September 5, 1887\n|[[Macleod (N.W.T. electoral district)|Macleod]] by-election\n|colspan=2 align=center|1\n|-\n|June 30, 1888\n|[[1888 Northwest Territories general election|1st general election]]\n|[[1st North-West Legislative Assembly|1st N-W Assembly]]\n|colspan=2 align=center|22\n|Chairman: [[Robert Brett]]\n|-\n|November 7, 1891\n|[[1891 Northwest Territories general election|2nd general election]]\n|[[2nd North-West Legislative Assembly|2nd N-W Assembly]]\n|colspan=2 align=center|25\n|rowspan=2|Chairman: [[Frederick W.A.G. Haultain|Frederick Haultain]]\n|-\n|October 31, 1894\n|[[1894 Northwest Territories general election|3rd general election]]\n|[[3rd North-West Legislative Assembly|3rd N-W Assembly]]\n|colspan=2 align=center|28\n|-\n|November 4, 1898\n|[[1898 Northwest Territories general election|4th general election]]<ref name=\"fifth\" group=\"Note\">The fourth and fifth general elections were the only general elections elected on party lines.</ref>\n|[[4th North-West Legislative Assembly|4th N-W Assembly]]\n|colspan=2 align=center|31\n|Premier: [[Frederick W.A.G. Haultain|Frederick Haultain]]<br />Opposition: [[Robert Brett]]\n|-\n|rowspan=4|May 21, 1902 \n|rowspan=4|[[1902 Northwest Territories general election|5th general election]]<ref name=\"fifth\" group=\"Note\" />\n|rowspan=4|[[5th North-West Legislative Assembly|5th N-W Assembly]]\n|{{Canadian_politics/party_colours/Progressive_Conservatives}}|\n|[[Northwest Territories Liberal-Conservative Party|Lib-Con.]] 21\n|rowspan=4 |Premier: [[Frederick W.A.G. Haultain|Frederick Haultain]]<br />Opposition: [[Donald H. McDonald|Donald McDonald]]\n|-\n|{{Canadian_politics/party_colours/Liberal}}|\n|[[Northwest Territories Liberal Party|Liberal]] 7\n|-\n|{{Canadian_politics/party_colours/Independents}}|\n|Ind. 6\n|-\n|{{Canadian_politics/party_colours/Independents}}|\n|Ind. Lib. 1\n|-\n|1905\n|colspan=6|Creation of [[Alberta]] and [[Saskatchewan]]\n|-\n|colspan=5 align=center|\n[[2nd Council of the Northwest Territories]], no elections 1905 - 1951\n|align=center rowspan=9|Appointed<br />[[List of Northwest Territories commissioners|Commissioner]]\n|rowspan=6|Ottawa\n|-\n|September 17, 1951\n|[[1951 Northwest Territories general election|6th general election]]\n|[[1st Northwest Territories Legislative Council|1st NWT Council]]\n|colspan=2 align=center|3\n|-\n|September 7, 1954\n|[[1954 Northwest Territories general election|7th general election]]\n|[[2nd Northwest Territories Legislative Council|2nd NWT Council]]\n|colspan=2 align=center|4\n|-\n|August 19, 1957\n|[[1957 Northwest Territories general election|8th general election]]\n|[[3rd Northwest Territories Legislative Council|3rd NWT Council]]\n|colspan=2 align=center|4\n|-\n|September 19, 1960\n|[[1960 Northwest Territories general election|9th general election]]\n|[[4th Northwest Territories Legislative Council|4th NWT Council]]\n|colspan=2 align=center|4\n|-\n|March 31, 1964\n|[[1964 Northwest Territories general election|10th general election]]\n|[[5th Northwest Territories Legislative Council|5th NWT Council]]\n|colspan=2 align=center|4\n|-\n|July 4, 1967\n|[[1967 Northwest Territories general election|11th general election]]\n|[[6th Northwest Territories Legislative Council|6th NWT Council]]\n|colspan=2 align=center|7\n|rowspan=14|[[Yellowknife, Northwest Territories|Yellowknife]]\n|-\n|December 21, 1970\n|[[1970 Northwest Territories general election|12th general election]]\n|[[7th Northwest Territories Legislative Council|7th NWT Council]]\n|colspan=2 align=center|10\n|-\n|March 10, 1975\n|[[1975 Northwest Territories general election|13th general election]]\n|[[8th Northwest Territories Legislative Assembly|8th NWT Assembly]]\n|colspan=2 align=center|15\n|-\n|October 1, 1979\n|[[1979 Northwest Territories general election|14th general election]]\n|[[9th Northwest Territories Legislative Assembly|9th NWT Assembly]]\n|colspan=2 align=center|22\n|Premier: [[George Braden]]\n|-\n|November 21, 1983\n|[[1983 Northwest Territories general election|15th general election]]\n|[[10th Northwest Territories Legislative Assembly|10th NWT Assembly]]\n|colspan=2 align=center|24\n|Premier: [[Richard Nerysoo]]\n|-\n|October 5, 1987\n|[[1987 Northwest Territories general election|16th general election]]\n|[[11th Northwest Territories Legislative Assembly|11th NWT Assembly]]\n|colspan=2 align=center|24\n|Premier: [[Dennis Patterson]]\n|-\n|October 15, 1991\n|[[1991 Northwest Territories general election|17th general election]]\n|[[12th Northwest Territories Legislative Assembly|12th NWT Assembly]]\n|colspan=2 align=center|24\n|Premier: [[Nellie Cournoyea]]\n|-\n|October 16, 1995\n|[[1995 Northwest Territories general election|18th general election]]\n|[[13th Northwest Territories Legislative Assembly|13th NWT Assembly]]\n|colspan=2 align=center|24\n|Premier: [[Don Morin]]\n|-\n|1999\n|colspan=5|Creation of [[Nunavut]]\n|-\n|December 6, 1999\n|[[1999 Northwest Territories general election|19th general election]]\n|[[14th Northwest Territories Legislative Assembly|14th NWT Assembly]]\n|colspan=2 align=center|19\n|Premier: [[Stephen Kakfwi]]\n|-\n|November 24, 2003\n|[[2003 Northwest Territories general election|20th general election]]\n|[[15th Northwest Territories Legislative Assembly|15th NWT Assembly]]\n|colspan=2 align=center|19\n|Premier: [[Joe Handley]]\n|-\n| October 1, 2007\n| [[2007 Northwest Territories general election|21st general election]]\n| [[16th Northwest Territories Legislative Assembly|16th NWT Assembly]]\n|colspan=2 align=\"center\"| 19\n| Premier: [[Floyd Roland]]\n|-\n| October 3, 2011\n| [[2011 Northwest Territories general election|22nd general election]]\n| [[17th Northwest Territories Legislative Assembly|17th NWT Assembly]]\n|colspan=2 align=\"center\"| 19\n| Premier: [[Bob McLeod (politician)|Bob McLeod]]\n|-\n| November 23, 2015\n| [[2015 Northwest Territories general election|23rd general election]]\n| [[18th Northwest Territories Legislative Assembly|18th NWT Assembly]]\n|colspan=2 align=\"center\"| 19\n| Premier: [[Bob McLeod (politician)|Bob McLeod]]\n|-\n| October 1, 2019\n| [[2019 Northwest Territories general election|24th general election]]\n| [[19th Northwest Territories Legislative Assembly|19th NWT Assembly]]\n|colspan=2 align=\"center\"| 19\n| Premier: [[Caroline Cochrane]]\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Alberta general elections]]\n*[[List of Saskatchewan general elections]]\n*[[List of Nunavut general elections]]\n*[[List of Yukon general elections]]\n*[[List of Northwest Territories Plebiscites]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=\"Note\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n<!--\n==Bibliography==\n Dead note \"rupertref\": [http://www.solon.org/Constitutions/Canada/English/tgrla_1869.html Temporary Government of Rupert's Land Act, 1869] accessed April 13, 2006-->\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.gov.nt.ca/ Government of Northwest Territories]\n*[http://www.electionsnwt.ca/ Elections Northwest Territories]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20051023021215/http://www.justice.gov.nt.ca/PDF/ACTS/Elections.pdf Northwest Territories Elections Act]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060214112848/http://www.assembly.gov.nt.ca/VisitorInfo/ImageGallery/CouncilsandAssemblies.html Councils and Assemblies of the Northwest Territories dates and photos from 1951 to present]\n*[http://www.rootsweb.com/~cansk/SaskatchewanAndItsPeople/Volume2/territorialassembly.html Personnel of Northwest Territories Assembly 1888 - 1905]\n\n{{Canelections}}\n{{Northwest Territories elections}}\n{{NWT-ED}}\n{{Northwest Territories politics}}\n\n[[Category:Elections in the Northwest Territories|*]]\n[[Category:Canadian election timelines|Northwest Territories general elections]]\n[[Category:Northwest Territories-related lists|Elections, general]]\n[[Category:Lists of elections in Canada|Northwest Territories]]\n", "name_user": "Toweli", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eList of elections", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Northwest_Territories_general_elections"}
{"title_page": "Abba Kyari", "text_new": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{For|the Nigerian Army Brigadier who served as Governor of North-Central State|Abba Kyari (military general)}}\n{{short description|Nigerian politician}}\n{{Use Nigerian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n| name                = Abba Kyari\n| image               = Abba-Kyari2.jpg\n| image_size          = \n| caption             = \n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1952|09|23|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = Borno, [[Northern Region, Nigeria|Northern Region]], [[British Nigeria]]<br>(now [[Borno State]], Nigeria)\n| death_date          = {{Death date and age|2020|4|17|1952|09|23|df=y}}\n| office1             = [[Chief of Staff to the President (Nigeria)| Chief of  Staff to the President]]\n| president1          = [[Muhammadu Buhari]]\n| term_start1         = 27 August 2015\n| term_end1           = 17 April 2020\n| predecessor1        = Jones Arogbofa\n| alma_mater          = [[Nigerian Law School]]<br>[[International Institute for Management Development]]\n| education           = [[University of Warwick]]<br>[[University of Cambridge]]\n| awards              = [[Order of the Niger]]\n| death_place         = [[Lagos]], Nigeria\n| honorific_suffix    = [[Order of the Niger|OON]]\n| spouse              = Hajiya Kulu Kyari\n| children            = 4\n}}\n\n'''Abba Kyari''' [[Order of the Niger|OON]] (23 September 1952*nbsp;\u2013 17 April 2020)<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/news/top-news/388646-exclusive-abba-kyaris-real-date-of-birth-uncovered.html |title=EXCLUSIVE: Abba Kyari's real date of birth uncovered |work=[[Premium Times]] |last=Ogundipe |first=Samuel |date=18 April 2020 |language=en-GB |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> was [[Chief of Staff to the President (Nigeria)|Chief of Staff to the President of Nigeria]] from August 2015 to April 2020.<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite web|last1=Bakare|first1=Tonye|title=Buhari appoints Lawal as SGF, Kyari as CoS|url=http://www.ngrguardiannews.com/2015/08/flash-buhari-appoints-lawal-as-sgf/|website=Guardian Nigeria|accessdate=29 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nKyari was born on 23 September 1952, to a [[Kanuri people|Kanuri]] family from [[Borno State|Borno]]. He was educated in St. Paul\u2019s College in [[Wusasa]], and later considered joining the [[Nigerian Army]] following advice from [[Mamman Daura]] and [[Ibrahim Tahir]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://guardian.ng/opinion/columnists/ibrahim-tahir-a-personal-loss-2/|title=Ibrahim Tahir: A Personal Loss|last=Kyari|first=Abba|date=23 December 2009|website=The Guardian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In 1976, he met General [[Muhammadu Buhari]] who was then [[Governor of Borno State]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://guardian.ng/features/for-the-record/to-my-friend-mallam-abba-kyari-buhari/|title=To my friend, Mallam Abba Kyari \u2013 Buhari|last=Buhari|first=Muhammadu|date=18 April 2020|website=The Guardian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nHe graduated with a [[bachelor's degree]] in [[sociology]] from the [[University of Warwick]] in 1980, and also obtained a [[law]] degree from the [[University of Cambridge]].<ref name=\"Exxon-Mobil2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.exxonmobil.com.ng/Nigeria-English/PA/products_downstream_directors.aspx|title=Exxon Mobil Nigeria Board of Directors|website=Exxon Mobil|accessdate=29 August 2015}}</ref> Kyari was called to the [[Nigerian Bar Association|Nigerian Bar]] in 1983 after attending the [[Nigerian Law School]].<ref name=\"TDLN\">{{cite web|last1=Aboyade |first1=Funke |title=From Dublin, Law School Set of \u201983 Plans Big |url=http://www.thisdaylive.com/articles/from-dublin-law-school-set-of-8217-83-plans-big/127530 |website=This Day Live Nigeria |accessdate=29 August 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016010128/http://www.thisdaylive.com/articles/from-dublin-law-school-set-of-8217-83-plans-big/127530 |archivedate=16 October 2012 }}</ref> \n\nIn 1984, he obtained a [[master's degree]] in law from the University of Cambridge.<ref name=\"Exxon-Mobil\">{{cite web|title=Exxon Mobil Nigeria Board of Directors|url=http://www.exxonmobil.com.ng/Nigeria-English/PA/products_downstream_directors.aspx|website=Exxon Mobil|accessdate=29 August 2015}}</ref> He later attended the [[International Institute for Management Development]] in [[Lausanne]], Switzerland,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-04-18/nigerian-president-s-chief-of-staff-abba-kyari-dies-of-covid-19 |title=Nigerian President's Chief of Staff Dies After Getting Virus |publisher=[[Bloomberg News]] |date=17 April 2020 |accessdate=19 April 2020 |author=Ibukun, Yinka and Alonso Soto}}</ref> and in 1992 and 1994 participated in the [[Harvard Business School]]'s Program for Leadership Development.<ref name=Litany>{{cite web |url=https://guardian.ng/politics/abba-kyari-a-litany-of-controversies/ |title=Abba Kyari: A litany of controversies |work=[[The Guardian (Nigeria)]] |date=19 April 2020 |accessdate=19 April 2020 |author=Olumide, Seye}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nKyari worked for the law firm Fani-Kayode and Sowemimo for some time after his return to Nigeria.<ref name=\"Naij-FFK\">{{cite web|last1=Bolashodun|first1=Oluwatobi|title=Fani-Kayode Reacts To Abba Kyari's Appointment|url=https://www.naij.com/532624-read-fani-kayodes-reaction-abba-kyaris-appointment-buharis-cos.html|website=Naij|accessdate=29 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1988 to 1990, he was Editor with the New Africa Holdings Limited Kaduna. He also served as a Commissioner for Forestry and Animal Resources in [[Borno State]] in 1990s.<ref name=\"LN\">{{cite web |title=Abba Kyari: The Man, The Mandate And The Mission |url=https://leadership.ng/2020/04/18/abba-kyari-the-man-the-mandate-and-the-mission-leadership-special/ |publisher=Leadership |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1990 to 1995, Kyari was the secretary to the board of African International Bank Limited, a subsidiary of [[Bank of Credit and Commerce International]].<ref name=\"LN\" />\n\nKyari was an executive director in charge of management services at the [[United Bank for Africa]], and was later appointed the [[chief executive officer]]. In 2002, he was appointed a board director of [[Unilever Nigeria Plc|Unilever Nigeria]], and later served on the board of [[ExxonMobil|Exxon Mobil]] Nigeria.<ref name=Litany/>\n\n=== Chief of Staff to the President ===\nIn August 2015, Kyari was appointed [[Chief of Staff to the President (Nigeria)|Chief of Staff]] to [[President of Nigeria|President]] [[Muhammadu Buhari]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.infoguideafrica.com/2020/04/Abba-Kyari.html|title=Mallam Abba Kyari Biography, Age, Early Life, Family, Net Worth And More|last=Stanford|first=Igbo|website=Information Guide Africa|access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/news/headlines/189095-breaking-buhari-appoints-sgf-chief-of-staff-others.html|title=Buhari appoints SGF, Chief of Staff, others - Premium Times Nigeria|date=27 August 2015|language=en-GB|access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nKyari was an influential figure within the Buhari administration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://punchng.com/men-of-power-nigerias-most-influential-power-brokers/|title=Men of power: Nigeria\u2019s most influential power brokers|last=Published|website=Punch Newspapers|language=en-US|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref> During the administration's first term, he worked mainly [[\u00c9minence grise|behind the scenes]] to implement the president's agenda.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/news/headlines/192601-in-surprise-move-saraki-personally-submits-names-of-ministers-to-buhari.html|title=In surprise move, Saraki personally submits names of ministers to Buhari - Premium Times Nigeria|date=3 November 2015|language=en-GB|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref> In [[2019 Nigerian general election|2019]] with Buhari's re-election for a second term, he ordered his [[Cabinet of Nigeria|cabinet]] to channel all requests through Kyari's office.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pmnewsnigeria.com/2019/08/21/go-through-abba-kyari-to-see-me-buhari-directs-ministers/|title=Go through Abba Kyari to see me, Buhari directs ministers - P.M. News|website=www.pmnewsnigeria.com|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref> Further enhancing his influence within government circles, and being labelled as the de facto head of government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://businessday.ng/lead-story/article/abba-kyari-prime-minister-in-a-presidential-system/|title=Abba Kyari: Prime minister in a presidential system|date=25 August 2019|website=Businessday NG|language=en-US|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, following a leaked memo, Kyari became embroiled in a public argument with the [[Nigerian Civil Service|Head of Civil Service]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelstv.com/2017/11/01/oyo-ita-kyari-heated-argument-villa/|title=Oyo-Ita, Kyari In Heated Argument At Presidential Villa|website=Channels Television|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref> who was later removed from office and arrested.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/news/headlines/353112-breaking-buhari-sacks-head-of-service-oyo-ita.html|title=Buhari sacks Head of Service, Oyo-Ita - Premium Times Nigeria|date=18 September 2019|language=en-GB|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/alleged-n570m-fraud-ex-head-of-service-oyo-ita-arrested/|title=Alleged N570m fraud: Ex-Head of Service Oyo-Ita arrested|last=Alli|first=Yusuf|date=23 March 2020|website=The Nation|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> In 2020, in another leaked memo, [[Babagana Monguno]] the [[National Security Advisor (Nigeria)|National Security Adviser]] accused Kyari of meddling in matters of national security.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/news/headlines/377757-updated-exclusive-buharis-team-in-disarray-as-nsa-monguno-declares-war-on-abba-kyari.html|title=UPDATED: EXCLUSIVE: Buhari\u2019s team in disarray as NSA Monguno declares war on Abba Kyari|last=Ogundipe|first=Samuel|date=17 February 2020|language=en-GB|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nKyari was married to the sister-in-law of [[Ibrahim Tahir]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gamji.com/haruna/haruna303.htm|title=Tahir: The Death of a Radical Conservative|last=Haruna|first=Mohammed|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and had four children.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://guardian.ng/opinion/columnists/ibrahim-tahir-a-personal-loss-2/|title=Ibrahim Tahir: A Personal Loss|last=Kyari|first=Abba|date=23 December 2009|website=The Guardian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March 2020, it was made public that Kyari tested positive for [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] on 23 March, following an official trip to Germany nine days before.<ref name=coronavirus>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/news/headlines/383571-coronavirus-abba-kyari-reportedly-tests-positive-kingibe-others-may-be-tested.html|title=UPDATED: Coronavirus: Abba Kyari reportedly tests positive; Kingibe, others may be tested|last=Owoseye|first=Ayodamola|date=24 March 2020|language=en-GB|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> There were reports that he had been flown out of the country for treatment,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://desertherald.com/exclusive-buharis-chief-of-staff-abba-kyari-admitted-at-londons-hospital/|title=EXCLUSIVE: Buhari\u2019s Chief of Staff, Abba Kyari Admitted at London\u2019s Hospital|last=Herald|first=Desert|language=en-US|access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> and [[Reuters]] later reported he had \"a history of medical complications, including [[diabetes]]\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-nigeria-idUSKBN21B1OT|title=Top Nigerian president aide, state governor test positive for coronavirus|date=24 March 2020|work=Reuters|access-date=18 April 2020|language=en}}</ref> On 29 March 2020, in an official statement, Kyari annouced he was being moved from isolation in [[Abuja]] to [[Lagos]] for \"preventive treatment\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailytrust.com.ng/covid-19-why-i-moved-to-lagos-after-testing-positive-abba-kyari.html|title=Covid-19: Why I moved to Lagos after testing positive - Abba Kyari|date=29 March 2020|website=Daily Trust|language=en-GB|access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nKyari died on the evening of 17 April 2020 at age 67.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://m.guardian.ng/breakingnews/buharis-chief-of-staff-abba-kyari-dies//|title=Buhari\u2019s Chief Of Staff Abba Kyari Dies|website=The Guardian Newspapers|access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Honours and awards ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|[[Order of the Niger|Officer of the Order of the Niger (OON)]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://dailypost.ng/2020/04/18/abba-kyari-10-things-to-know-about-buharis-late-chief-of-staff/ |title=Abba Kyari: 10 things to know about Buhari's late Chief of Staff |work=[[Daily Post (Nigeria)|Daily Post]] |date=18 April 2020 |accessdate=19 April 2020 |author=Nseyen, Nsikak}}</ref> [[File:Ribbon bar of the Order of the Niger.gif|frameless|59x59px]]\n|National honour in Nigeria\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kyari, Abba}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Nigerian Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Warwick]]\n[[Category:International Institute for Management Development alumni]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Niger]]\n[[Category:Nigerian lawyers]]\n[[Category:Kanuri people]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{For|the Nigerian Army Brigadier who served as Governor of North-Central State|Abba Kyari (military general)}}\n{{short description|Nigerian politician}}\n{{Use Nigerian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n| name                = Abba Kyari\n| image               = Abba-Kyari2.jpg\n| image_size          = \n| caption             = \n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1952|09|23|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = Borno, [[Northern Region, Nigeria|Northern Region]], [[British Nigeria]]<br>(now [[Borno State]], Nigeria)\n| death_date          = {{Death date and age|2020|4|17|1952|09|23|df=y}}\n| office1             = [[Chief of Staff to the President (Nigeria)| Chief of  Staff to the President]]\n| president1          = [[Muhammadu Buhari]]\n| term_start1         = 27 August 2015\n| term_end1           = 17 April 2020\n| predecessor1        = Jones Arogbofa\n| alma_mater          = [[Nigerian Law School]]<br>[[International Institute for Management Development]]\n| education           = [[University of Warwick]]<br>[[University of Cambridge]]\n| awards              = [[Order of the Niger]]\n| death_place         = [[Lagos]], Nigeria\n| honorific_suffix    = [[Order of the Niger|OON]]\n| spouse              = Hajiya Kulu Kyari\n| children            = 4\n}}\n\n'''Abba Kyari''' [[Order of the Niger|OON]] (23 September 1952 \u2013 17 April 2020)<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/news/top-news/388646-exclusive-abba-kyaris-real-date-of-birth-uncovered.html |title=EXCLUSIVE: Abba Kyari's real date of birth uncovered |work=[[Premium Times]] |last=Ogundipe |first=Samuel |date=18 April 2020 |language=en-GB |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> was [[Chief of Staff to the President (Nigeria)|Chief of Staff to the President of Nigeria]] from August 2015 to April 2020.<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite web|last1=Bakare|first1=Tonye|title=Buhari appoints Lawal as SGF, Kyari as CoS|url=http://www.ngrguardiannews.com/2015/08/flash-buhari-appoints-lawal-as-sgf/|website=Guardian Nigeria|accessdate=29 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nKyari was born on 23 September 1952, to a [[Kanuri people|Kanuri]] family from [[Borno State|Borno]]. He was educated in St. Paul\u2019s College in [[Wusasa]], and later considered joining the [[Nigerian Army]] following advice from [[Mamman Daura]] and [[Ibrahim Tahir]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://guardian.ng/opinion/columnists/ibrahim-tahir-a-personal-loss-2/|title=Ibrahim Tahir: A Personal Loss|last=Kyari|first=Abba|date=23 December 2009|website=The Guardian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In 1976, he met General [[Muhammadu Buhari]] who was then [[Governor of Borno State]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://guardian.ng/features/for-the-record/to-my-friend-mallam-abba-kyari-buhari/|title=To my friend, Mallam Abba Kyari \u2013 Buhari|last=Buhari|first=Muhammadu|date=18 April 2020|website=The Guardian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nHe graduated with a [[bachelor's degree]] in [[sociology]] from the [[University of Warwick]] in 1980, and also obtained a [[law]] degree from the [[University of Cambridge]].<ref name=\"Exxon-Mobil2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.exxonmobil.com.ng/Nigeria-English/PA/products_downstream_directors.aspx|title=Exxon Mobil Nigeria Board of Directors|website=Exxon Mobil|accessdate=29 August 2015}}</ref> Kyari was called to the [[Nigerian Bar Association|Nigerian Bar]] in 1983 after attending the [[Nigerian Law School]].<ref name=\"TDLN\">{{cite web|last1=Aboyade |first1=Funke |title=From Dublin, Law School Set of \u201983 Plans Big |url=http://www.thisdaylive.com/articles/from-dublin-law-school-set-of-8217-83-plans-big/127530 |website=This Day Live Nigeria |accessdate=29 August 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016010128/http://www.thisdaylive.com/articles/from-dublin-law-school-set-of-8217-83-plans-big/127530 |archivedate=16 October 2012 }}</ref> \n\nIn 1984, he obtained a [[master's degree]] in law from the University of Cambridge.<ref name=\"Exxon-Mobil\">{{cite web|title=Exxon Mobil Nigeria Board of Directors|url=http://www.exxonmobil.com.ng/Nigeria-English/PA/products_downstream_directors.aspx|website=Exxon Mobil|accessdate=29 August 2015}}</ref> He later attended the [[International Institute for Management Development]] in [[Lausanne]], Switzerland,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-04-18/nigerian-president-s-chief-of-staff-abba-kyari-dies-of-covid-19 |title=Nigerian President's Chief of Staff Dies After Getting Virus |publisher=[[Bloomberg News]] |date=17 April 2020 |accessdate=19 April 2020 |author=Ibukun, Yinka and Alonso Soto}}</ref> and in 1992 and 1994 participated in the [[Harvard Business School]]'s Program for Leadership Development.<ref name=Litany>{{cite web |url=https://guardian.ng/politics/abba-kyari-a-litany-of-controversies/ |title=Abba Kyari: A litany of controversies |work=[[The Guardian (Nigeria)]] |date=19 April 2020 |accessdate=19 April 2020 |author=Olumide, Seye}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nKyari worked for the law firm Fani-Kayode and Sowemimo for some time after his return to Nigeria.<ref name=\"Naij-FFK\">{{cite web|last1=Bolashodun|first1=Oluwatobi|title=Fani-Kayode Reacts To Abba Kyari's Appointment|url=https://www.naij.com/532624-read-fani-kayodes-reaction-abba-kyaris-appointment-buharis-cos.html|website=Naij|accessdate=29 August 2015}}</ref>  \n\nFrom 1988 to 1990, he was Editor with the New Africa Holdings Limited Kaduna.  He also served as a Commissioner for Forestry and Animal Resources in [[Borno State]] in 1990s.<ref name=\"LN\">{{cite web |title=Abba Kyari: The Man, The Mandate And The Mission |url=https://leadership.ng/2020/04/18/abba-kyari-the-man-the-mandate-and-the-mission-leadership-special/ |publisher=Leadership |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1990 to 1995, Kyari was the secretary to the board of African International Bank Limited, a subsidiary of [[Bank of Credit and Commerce International]].<ref name=\"LN\" />\n\nKyari was an executive director in charge of management services at the [[United Bank for Africa]], and was later appointed the [[chief executive officer]]. In 2002, he was appointed a board director of [[Unilever Nigeria Plc|Unilever Nigeria]], and later served on the board of [[ExxonMobil|Exxon Mobil]] Nigeria.<ref name=Litany/>\n\n=== Chief of Staff to the President ===\nIn August 2015, Kyari was appointed [[Chief of Staff to the President (Nigeria)|Chief of Staff]] to [[President of Nigeria|President]] [[Muhammadu Buhari]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.infoguideafrica.com/2020/04/Abba-Kyari.html|title=Mallam Abba Kyari Biography, Age, Early Life, Family, Net Worth And More|last=Stanford|first=Igbo|website=Information Guide Africa|access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/news/headlines/189095-breaking-buhari-appoints-sgf-chief-of-staff-others.html|title=Buhari appoints SGF, Chief of Staff, others - Premium Times Nigeria|date=27 August 2015|language=en-GB|access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nKyari was an influential figure within the Buhari administration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://punchng.com/men-of-power-nigerias-most-influential-power-brokers/|title=Men of power: Nigeria\u2019s most influential power brokers|last=Published|website=Punch Newspapers|language=en-US|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref> During the administration's first term, he worked mainly [[\u00c9minence grise|behind the scenes]] to implement the president's agenda.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/news/headlines/192601-in-surprise-move-saraki-personally-submits-names-of-ministers-to-buhari.html|title=In surprise move, Saraki personally submits names of ministers to Buhari - Premium Times Nigeria|date=3 November 2015|language=en-GB|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref> In [[2019 Nigerian general election|2019]] with Buhari's re-election for a second term, he ordered his [[Cabinet of Nigeria|cabinet]] to channel all requests through Kyari's office.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pmnewsnigeria.com/2019/08/21/go-through-abba-kyari-to-see-me-buhari-directs-ministers/|title=Go through Abba Kyari to see me, Buhari directs ministers - P.M. News|website=www.pmnewsnigeria.com|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref> Further enhancing his influence within government circles, and being labelled as the de facto head of government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://businessday.ng/lead-story/article/abba-kyari-prime-minister-in-a-presidential-system/|title=Abba Kyari: Prime minister in a presidential system|date=25 August 2019|website=Businessday NG|language=en-US|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, following a leaked memo, Kyari became embroiled in a public argument with the [[Nigerian Civil Service|Head of Civil Service]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelstv.com/2017/11/01/oyo-ita-kyari-heated-argument-villa/|title=Oyo-Ita, Kyari In Heated Argument At Presidential Villa|website=Channels Television|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref> who was later removed from office and arrested.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/news/headlines/353112-breaking-buhari-sacks-head-of-service-oyo-ita.html|title=Buhari sacks Head of Service, Oyo-Ita - Premium Times Nigeria|date=18 September 2019|language=en-GB|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/alleged-n570m-fraud-ex-head-of-service-oyo-ita-arrested/|title=Alleged N570m fraud: Ex-Head of Service Oyo-Ita arrested|last=Alli|first=Yusuf|date=23 March 2020|website=The Nation|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> In 2020, in another leaked memo, [[Babagana Monguno]] the [[National Security Advisor (Nigeria)|National Security Adviser]] accused Kyari of meddling in matters of national security.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/news/headlines/377757-updated-exclusive-buharis-team-in-disarray-as-nsa-monguno-declares-war-on-abba-kyari.html|title=UPDATED: EXCLUSIVE: Buhari\u2019s team in disarray as NSA Monguno declares war on Abba Kyari|last=Ogundipe|first=Samuel|date=17 February 2020|language=en-GB|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nKyari was married to the sister-in-law of [[Ibrahim Tahir]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gamji.com/haruna/haruna303.htm|title=Tahir: The Death of a Radical Conservative|last=Haruna|first=Mohammed|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and had four children.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://guardian.ng/opinion/columnists/ibrahim-tahir-a-personal-loss-2/|title=Ibrahim Tahir: A Personal Loss|last=Kyari|first=Abba|date=23 December 2009|website=The Guardian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March 2020, it was made public that Kyari tested positive for [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] on 23 March, following an official trip to Germany nine days before.<ref name=coronavirus>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/news/headlines/383571-coronavirus-abba-kyari-reportedly-tests-positive-kingibe-others-may-be-tested.html|title=UPDATED: Coronavirus: Abba Kyari reportedly tests positive; Kingibe, others may be tested|last=Owoseye|first=Ayodamola|date=24 March 2020|language=en-GB|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> There were reports that he had been flown out of the country for treatment,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://desertherald.com/exclusive-buharis-chief-of-staff-abba-kyari-admitted-at-londons-hospital/|title=EXCLUSIVE: Buhari\u2019s Chief of Staff, Abba Kyari Admitted at London\u2019s Hospital|last=Herald|first=Desert|language=en-US|access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> and [[Reuters]] later reported he had \"a history of medical complications, including [[diabetes]]\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-nigeria-idUSKBN21B1OT|title=Top Nigerian president aide, state governor test positive for coronavirus|date=24 March 2020|work=Reuters|access-date=18 April 2020|language=en}}</ref> On 29 March 2020, in an official statement, Kyari annouced he was being moved from isolation in [[Abuja]] to [[Lagos]] for \"preventive treatment\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailytrust.com.ng/covid-19-why-i-moved-to-lagos-after-testing-positive-abba-kyari.html|title=Covid-19: Why I moved to Lagos after testing positive - Abba Kyari|date=29 March 2020|website=Daily Trust|language=en-GB|access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nKyari died on the evening of 17 April 2020 at age 67.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://m.guardian.ng/breakingnews/buharis-chief-of-staff-abba-kyari-dies//|title=Buhari\u2019s Chief Of Staff Abba Kyari Dies|website=The Guardian Newspapers|access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Honours and awards ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|[[Order of the Niger|Officer of the Order of the Niger (OON)]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://dailypost.ng/2020/04/18/abba-kyari-10-things-to-know-about-buharis-late-chief-of-staff/ |title=Abba Kyari: 10 things to know about Buhari's late Chief of Staff |work=[[Daily Post (Nigeria)|Daily Post]] |date=18 April 2020 |accessdate=19 April 2020 |author=Nseyen, Nsikak}}</ref> [[File:Ribbon bar of the Order of the Niger.gif|frameless|59x59px]]\n|National honour in Nigeria\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kyari, Abba}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Nigerian Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Warwick]]\n[[Category:International Institute for Management Development alumni]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Niger]]\n[[Category:Nigerian lawyers]]\n[[Category:Kanuri people]]\n", "name_user": "JHunterJ", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abba_Kyari"}
{"title_page": "Paul Huldschinsky", "text_new": "{{short description|Set decorator}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Paul Huldschinsky\n| image        =\n| birth_date   = 18 August 1889\n| birth_place  = [[Berlin]]\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|1947|2|1|1889|8|18|df=yes}}\n| death_place  = [[Santa Monica, California]]\n| occupation   = [[Set decorator]]\n| yearsactive  = 1940-1947\n}}\n\n'''Paul Huldschinsky''' (18 August 1889 &ndash; 1 February 1947) was a German-Jewish architect and [[set decorator]]. After imprisonment in the [[Sachsenhausen concentration camp]] in 1938 he fled [[Nazi Germany]] in 1939 for California. He won an [[Academy Awards|Oscar]] in the category [[Academy Award for Best Production Design|Best Art Direction]] for the film ''[[Gaslight (1944 film)|Gaslight]]''.<ref name=\"Oscars1945\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1945 |title=The 17th Academy Awards (1945) Nominees and Winners |accessdate=14 August 2011 |work=oscars.org |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706093748/http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/legacy/ceremony/17th-winners.html |archivedate=6 July 2011 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\n==Selected filmography==\n* ''[[Gaslight (1944 film)|Gaslight]]'' (1944)\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of German-speaking Academy Award winners and nominees]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0401344|Paul Huldschinsky}}\n*{{Amg name|161482|Paul Huldschinsky}}\n\n{{Academy Award Best Production Design}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Huldschinsky, Paul}}\n[[Category:1889 births]]\n[[Category:1947 deaths]]\n[[Category:German set decorators]]\n[[Category:Best Art Direction Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:German emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Jewish emigrants from Nazi Germany to the United States]]\n[[Category:Architects from Berlin\u200e]]\n[[Category:Sachsenhausen concentration camp survivors]]\n\n{{Germany-film-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Set decorator}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Paul Huldschinsky\n| image        =\n| birth_date   = 18 August 1889\n| birth_place  = [[Berlin]]\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|1947|2|1|1889|8|18|df=yes}}\n| death_place  = [[Santa Monica, California]]\n| occupation   = [[Set decorator]]\n| yearsactive  = 1940-1947\n}}\n\n'''Paul Huldschinsky''' (18 August 1889 &ndash; 1 February 1947) was a German-Jewish architect and [[set decorator]]. After imprisonment in the [[Sachsenhausen concentration camp]] in 1938 he fled [[Nazi Germany]] in 1939 for California. He won an [[Academy Awards|Oscar]] in the category [[Academy Award for Best Production Design|Best Art Direction]] for the film ''[[Gaslight (1944 film)|Gaslight]]''.<ref name=\"Oscars1945\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1945 |title=The 17th Academy Awards (1945) Nominees and Winners |accessdate=14 August 2011 |work=oscars.org |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706093748/http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/legacy/ceremony/17th-winners.html |archivedate=6 July 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Selected filmography==\n* ''[[Gaslight (1944 film)|Gaslight]]'' (1944)\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of German-speaking Academy Award winners and nominees]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0401344|Paul Huldschinsky}}\n*{{Amg name|161482|Paul Huldschinsky}}\n\n{{Academy Award Best Production Design}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Huldschinsky, Paul}}\n[[Category:1889 births]]\n[[Category:1947 deaths]]\n[[Category:German set decorators]]\n[[Category:Best Art Direction Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:German emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Jewish emigrants from Nazi Germany to the United States]]\n[[Category:Architects from Berlin\u200e]]\n[[Category:Sachsenhausen concentration camp survivors]]\n\n{{Germany-film-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Huldschinsky"}
{"title_page": "Steve Kerr", "text_new": "{{About||the Scottish footballer|Steven Kerr|the Scottish politician|Stephen Kerr}}\n{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American basketball player and coach}}\n{{Use American English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Steve Kerr\n| image = Steve Kerr (16453076458) cropped.jpg\n| caption = Kerr as the Warriors' head coach in February 2015\n| position = Head coach\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 1\n| height_footnote = <ref name=\"SKNBA\">{{cite web|url=https://stats.nba.com/player/70/career/|title=Steve Kerr|publisher=[[National Basketball Association]]|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n| weight_lb = 180\n| weight_footnote = <ref name=\"SKNBA\"/>\n| league = [[National Basketball Association|NBA]]\n| team = Golden State Warriors\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1965|09|27}}\n| birth_place = [[Beirut]], Lebanon\n| nationality = American\n| high_school = [[Palisades Charter High School|Palisades Charter]]<br />([[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, California]])\n| college = [[Arizona Wildcats men's basketball|Arizona]] (1983\u20131988)\n| draft_year = 1988\n| draft_round = 2\n| draft_pick = 50\n| draft_team = [[Phoenix Suns]]\n| career_start = 1988\n| career_end = 2003\n| career_position = [[Point guard]]\n| career_number = 4, 5, 2, 25\n| coach_start = 2014\n| years1 = {{nbay|1988|full=y}}\n| team1 = [[Phoenix Suns]]\n| years2 = {{nbay|1989|start}}\u2013{{nbay|1991|end}}\n| team2 = [[Cleveland Cavaliers]]\n| years3 = {{nbay|1992|full=y}}\n| team3 = [[Orlando Magic]]\n| years4 = {{nbay|1993|start}}\u2013{{nbay|1997|end}}\n| team4 = [[Chicago Bulls]]\n| years5 = {{nbay|1998|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2000|end}}\n| team5 = [[San Antonio Spurs]]\n| years6 = {{nbay|2001|full=y}}\n| team6 = [[Portland Trail Blazers]]\n| years7 = {{nbay|2002|full=y}}\n| team7 = San Antonio Spurs\n| cyears1 = {{nbay|2014|start}}\u2013present\n| cteam1 = [[Golden State Warriors]]\n| highlights = \n'''As player:'''\n* 5\u00d7 [[NBA champion]] ([[1996 NBA Finals|1996]]\u2013[[1999 NBA Finals|1999]], [[2003 NBA Finals|2003]])\n* [[NBA Three-Point Contest]] champion ([[1997 NBA All-Star Game|1997]])\n* Second-team [[NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|All-American]] \u2013 [[Associated Press|AP]] ([[1988 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1988]])\n* Third-team All-American \u2013 [[National Association of Basketball Coaches|NABC]] (1988)\n* 2\u00d7 First-team [[List of All-Pacific-12 Conference men's basketball teams|All-Pac-10]] (1986, 1988)\n* No. 25 [[Arizona Wildcats men's basketball#Retired numbers|retired by Arizona Wildcats]]\n'''As coach:'''\n* 3\u00d7 NBA champion ([[2015 NBA Finals|2015]], [[2017 NBA Finals|2017]], [[2018 NBA Finals|2018]])\n* [[NBA Coach of the Year Award|NBA Coach of the Year]] ({{nbay|2015|end}})\n* 2\u00d7 [[NBA All-Star Game head coach]] ([[2015 NBA All-Star Game|2015]], [[2017 NBA All-Star Game|2017]])\n| stat1label = [[Point (basketball)|Points]]\n| stat1value = 5,437 (6.0 ppg)\n| stat2label = [[Rebound (basketball)|Rebounds]]\n| stat2value = 1,060 (1.2 rpg)\n| stat3label = [[Assist (basketball)|Assists]]\n| stat3value = 1,658 (1.8 apg)\n| bbr = kerrst01\n| medal_templates = {{MedalSport | Men's [[basketball]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{flagu|United States}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA World Championship]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[1986 FIBA World Championship|1986 Spain]] | [[USA national basketball team|National team]]}}\n}}\n'''Stephen Douglas Kerr''' (born September 27, 1965) is an American professional [[basketball]] coach and former player who is the head coach of the [[Golden State Warriors]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/statistics/default_all_time_leaders/AllTimeLeadersFG3PQuery.html?topic=4&stat=6%7ctitle=NBA.com/Stats%7cwork=nba.com%7ctitle=NBA.com/Stats%7cwork=nba.com%7ctitle=NBA.com/Stats%7cwork=nba.com%7ctitle=NBA.com/Stats%7cwork=nba.com|title=NBA.com/Stats|work=nba.com}}</ref> He is an eight-time [[NBA champion]], having won five titles as a player (three with the [[Chicago Bulls]] and two with the [[San Antonio Spurs]]) as well as three with the Warriors as a head coach. Kerr has the highest career three-point percentage (45.4%) in NBA history for any player with at least 250 three-pointers made. He also held the NBA record for highest three-point percentage in a season at 52.4% until the record was broken by [[Kyle Korver]] in 2010.\n\nOn June 2, 2007, the [[Phoenix Suns]] named Kerr the team's president of basketball operations and general manager. Kerr helped managing partner [[Robert Sarver]] buy the Suns in 2004 and became one of Sarver's trusted basketball advisors. Kerr announced his retirement from the Suns in June 2010. Afterwards, Kerr returned as a color commentator for ''[[NBA on TNT]]'' until 2014, when he pursued a career in coaching.\n\nOn May 14, 2014, the [[Golden State Warriors]] named Kerr the team's head coach. On April 4, 2015, with a win over the [[Dallas Mavericks]], Kerr broke the NBA record for the most regular-season wins for a rookie coach. The Warriors went on to win the [[2015 NBA Finals]], making Kerr the first rookie coach to win a championship since [[Pat Riley]] in the [[1982 NBA Finals]]. On April 13, 2016, the Warriors broke the record for the [[List of NBA teams by single season win percentage|most wins in an NBA season]], breaking a record previously held by Kerr's [[1995\u201396 Chicago Bulls season|1995\u201396 Chicago Bulls]]. The Warriors returned to the Finals for five straight years, winning in [[2015 NBA Finals|2015]], losing in [[2016 NBA Finals|2016]], winning again in [[2017 NBA Finals|2017]] and [[2018 NBA Finals|2018]], and losing in [[2019 NBA Finals|2019]].\n\n==Early life==\nKerr was born in Beirut, Lebanon to [[Malcolm H. Kerr]], an American academic who specialized in the Middle East, and his wife, Ann (Zwicker).<ref name=\"chicagotribune.com\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1993-10-24/features/9310250053_1_malcolm-kerr-ann-kerr-arab-world|title=A Separate Peace|work=tribunedigital-chicagotribune}}</ref> He has three siblings.<ref name=\"nypost.com\">{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2014/05/03/in-the-wake-of-his-dads-assassination-kerr-became-a-champion/|title=Despite pain of dad's murder, Kerr became a champion \u2013 New York Post|work=New York Post}}</ref> His grandfather, [[Stanley Kerr]], volunteered with the [[Near East Foundation|Near East Relief]] after the [[Armenian Genocide]] and rescued women and orphans in [[Aleppo]] and [[Kahramanmara\u015f|Marash]] before eventually settling in [[Beirut]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://uproxx.com/dimemag/steve-kerr-middle-east-armenia-warriors/|title=The Inside Story Of Steve Kerr And His Family's Little-Known History Of Altruism In The Middle East|date=May 25, 2016|website=UPROXX|language=en-GB|access-date=June 3, 2016}}</ref> Kerr spent much of his childhood in [[Lebanon]] and other Middle Eastern countries. He attended [[Cairo American College]] in [[Egypt]], the [[American Community School Beirut|American Community School]] in Beirut, Lebanon, and Palisades High School (now [[Palisades Charter High School]]) in Los Angeles, graduating in 1983.\n\nMalcolm Kerr was killed by members of the [[List of militias in the Lebanese Civil War|Shia Lebanese militia]] called [[Islamic Jihad Organization|Islamic Jihad]] on the morning of January 18, 1984 at the age of 52 while he was serving as president of the [[American University of Beirut]].<ref name=\"nytimes.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/05/sports/basketball/steve-kerr-and-david-blatt-reached-nba-finals-on-unconventional-paths.html|title=Steve Kerr and David Blatt Reached N.B.A. Finals on Unconventional Paths|author=|date=June 5, 2015|work=The New York Times|accessdate=April 14, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"losangelestimes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/nba/la-sp-steve-kerr-dwyre-20150602-column.html|title=Bill Dwyre: Steve Kerr is defined as a person by much more than basketball|author=Los Angeles Times|date=June 1, 2015|work=latimes.com}}</ref><ref name=\"usatoday.com\">{{cite web|url=http://ftw.usatoday.com/2015/06/the-assassination-of-steve-kerrs-father-and-the-unlikely-story-of-a-champion|title=The assassination of Steve Kerr's father and the unlikely story of a champion \u2013 For The Win|work=For The Win}}</ref><ref name=\"mercurynews.com\">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.mercurynews.com/collegesports/2015/05/18/warriors-coach-steve-kerr-guided-by-his-fathers-life-and-lessons/|title=Warriors coach Steve Kerr guided by his father's life and lessons|work=mercurynews.com}}</ref> He was shot twice in the back of his head, by gunmen using suppressed handguns, in the hallway outside his office.<ref name=\"nypost.com\"/><ref name=\"losangelestimes\"/><ref name=\"usatoday.com\"/><ref name=\"mercurynews.com\"/> Kerr was 18 years old at the time, and a college freshman;<ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/> regarding his father's death, he has said: \"Before my father was killed, my life was impenetrable. Bad things happened to other people.\"<ref name=\"chicagotribune.com\"/> The Kerr family sued the Iranian government under the [[Antiterrorism and Effective Death Penalty Act of 1996]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Sports/nba-finals-rookie-coaches-golden-state-warriors-steve/story?id=31636589|title=NBA Finals' Rookie Coaches: Golden State Warriors' Steve Kerr and Cleveland Cavaliers' David Blatt|author=|work=ABC News}}</ref> While warming up with the Arizona Wildcats for a game at arch-rival Arizona State in 1988, Kerr had to deal with many ASU Sun Devil fans in the crowd chanting \"[[PLO]]\" and \"your father's history.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/05/sports/basketball/steve-kerr-and-david-blatt-reached-nba-finals-on-unconventional-paths.html|title=Steve Kerr and David Blatt Reached N.B.A. Finals on Unconventional Paths|work=nytimes.com}}</ref><ref name=\"go.com\">{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/new-york/nba/story/_/id/10895607/golden-state-warriors-steve-kerr-tough-enough-nba-coaching|title=Golden State Warriors' Steve Kerr is tough enough for NBA coaching|work=ESPN}}</ref> Though tearful, Kerr led the Wildcats to victory, scoring 20 points in the first half, making all six of his three-point attempts.<ref name=\"go.com\"/> The athletic director of Arizona State, Charles Harris, sent a letter of apology to Kerr a few days later.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dodds|first1=Tracy|title=Arizona St. Apologizes to Kerr: Arizona Guard Was Target of Taunts by Fans Before Game|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1988-03-01/sports/sp-257_1_arizona-state|website=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=July 19, 2016|date=March 1, 1988}}</ref>\n\nKerr graduated from the [[University of Arizona]] in 1988 with a [[Bachelor of General Studies]], with emphasis on history, sociology and English.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wc.arizona.edu/papers/97/150/01_1.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060915102058/http://wc.arizona.edu/papers/97/150/01_1.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=September 15, 2006|title=Arizona Daily Wildcat \u2013 Steve Kerr ready for grad speech, tortillas|date=May 12, 2004|work=arizona.edu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/coachfile/steve_kerr/|title=Steve Kerr|work=nba.com}}</ref>\n\n==Collegiate career==\nMinimally recruited out of high school, Kerr played basketball for the [[University of Arizona]] from 1983 to 1988. In the summer of 1986, Kerr was named to the [[USA Basketball]] team that competed in the [[FIBA World Championship]] in Spain. The team was the last American Men's Senior Team composed strictly of [[amateur]] players to capture a gold medal. He blew out his knee in the tournament, usually a career-ending injury, forcing him to miss an entire season (1986\u201387) at Arizona.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1986-07-25-sp-119-story.html|title=Healing Process Is Mental for Kerr, Too : He's Haunted by Knee Injury Suffered in World Basketball Championships|date=1986-07-25|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref> He helped the Wildcats reach the [[NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Championship|Final Four]] of the NCAA Division I basketball tournament in 1988 along with fellow [[NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|All-American]] teammate [[Sean Elliott]]. Kerr also set an NCAA record for 3-point percentage in a season (114\u2013199, 57.3%).\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===Career beginnings===\nKerr was selected by the [[Phoenix Suns]] in the second round of the [[1988 NBA draft]]. He was traded to the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]] in 1989. He spent over three seasons (1989\u20131992) there and then part of the [[1992\u201393 NBA season|1992\u201393]] season with the [[Orlando Magic]].\n\n===Chicago Bulls===\nIn 1993, he signed with the [[Chicago Bulls]]. The Bulls made the playoffs in the [[1993\u201394 NBA season|1993\u201394]] and [[1994\u201395 NBA season|1994\u201395]] seasons, but without [[Michael Jordan]]'s presence for all of 1994 and much of 1995, the team could not advance to the Finals. However, with Jordan back full-time for the [[1995\u201396 NBA season|1995\u201396 season]], the Bulls set a then NBA-record of 72\u201310 and defeated the [[Seattle SuperSonics]] in the [[1996 NBA Finals]].\n\nKerr played a major part of the Bulls' championship victory in the [[1997 NBA Finals]] against the [[Utah Jazz]]. In the final seconds of Game 6 with the score tied at 86, he took a pass from Jordan and hit the title-winner. The Bulls won, earning the franchise's fifth title. Kerr also won the 3-Point Shootout at the 1997 All-Star Game.\n\nIn the last minute of Game 2 of the [[1998 NBA Finals]] against Utah, Kerr missed a 3-pointer, grabbed his own rebound and made a pass to Jordan who made a crucial three-point play, putting them in the lead for good. The play helped Chicago win the game and tie the series at 1. The Bulls won the series in 6 games.\n\n===San Antonio Spurs===\nIn January 1999, Kerr was acquired by the [[San Antonio Spurs]] in a sign-and-trade deal with the Bulls, whereby [[Chuck Person]] and a first-round pick in the [[2000 NBA draft]] was sent to Chicago.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://basketball.realgm.com/player/Steve-Kerr/Summary/1303|title=Steve Kerr Player Profile|work=RealGM.com|access-date=November 19, 2017}}</ref> The Spurs reached [[1999 NBA Finals]] and won their first NBA Championship with a 4\u20131 series victory over the [[New York Knicks]]. Kerr became the second player to win four straight NBA titles without being a part of the 1960s [[Boston Celtics]] dynasty, the other being [[Frank Saul (basketball)|Frank Saul]], who won four straight with Rochester and Minneapolis from 1951 to 1954.<ref>{{cite book|title=Basketball Championships' Most Wanted|first=David L.|last=Hudson, Jr.|date=February 2007|publisher=Potomac Books, Inc|page=[https://archive.org/details/basketballchampi0000huds/page/41 41]|isbn=1-59797-014-X|url=https://archive.org/details/basketballchampi0000huds/page/41}}</ref> Kerr and Saul were the only two players in NBA history to have won two championships with two different teams in consecutive seasons until [[Patrick McCaw]] achieved the same feat in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/2014/05/14/steve-kerr-career-highlights/|title=Steve Kerr career highlights|work=mercurynews.com|date=May 14, 2014|access-date=November 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fox2now.com/2019/06/13/st-louis-native-patrick-mccaw-wins-nba-championship-with-toronto-raptors/|title=St. Louis native Patrick McCaw wins NBA Championship with Toronto Raptors|date=2019-06-14|website=FOX2now.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref>\n\n===Portland Trail Blazers===\nKerr was traded to the Portland Trail Blazers alongside [[Derek Anderson (basketball)|Derek Anderson]] on July 24, 2001 in a deal that brought [[Steve Smith (basketball)|Steve Smith]] to the Spurs. He would remain in Portland for the [[2001\u201302 NBA season|2001\u201302]] season, playing in 65 games.\n\n===Return to the Spurs===\nOn August 2, 2002, Kerr was traded back to San Antonio along with [[Erick Barkley]] and a 2003 second-round pick. In return, the Trail Blazers received [[Charles Smith (basketball, born 1975)|Charles Smith]], [[Amal McCaskill]], and [[Antonio Daniels]]. Kerr played in nearly every game (75) the following year, which was his final season in the league.<ref>[http://basketball.realgm.com/player/Steve-Kerr/Summary/1303 basketball.realgm.com, accessed May 16, 2015.]</ref> In Game Six of the [[2003 NBA Playoffs|2003 Western Conference Finals]] against the [[Dallas Mavericks]], Kerr made four second-half three-pointers that helped eliminate Dallas. The Spurs eventually won the NBA championship by beating the [[New Jersey Nets]] in the [[2003 NBA Finals]], 4\u20132.\n\n===Retirement===\nKerr announced his retirement after the 2003 NBA Finals. During his NBA career, he played 910 regular-season games. He retired as the league's all-time leader in single-season three-point shooting percentage (.524 in 1994\u201395) and career three-point shooting percentage (.454). Kerr won a total of five NBA championships as a player.\n\n==Broadcaster and commentator==\n[[File:Steve Kerr 2013.jpg|thumb|Kerr in 2013]]\nIn 2003, Kerr became a broadcast analyst for [[TNT (U.S. TV network)|Turner Network Television]] (TNT), offering commentary alongside renowned analyst [[Marv Albert]]. During his tenure, he performed a segment sponsored by [[Coors Light]] called ''Steve's Refreshing Thoughts'' in which he brought up interesting facts in NBA history. This segment continued through sponsorship, and became known as ''Steve Wonders'', sponsored by [[Sprint Nextel|Sprint]]. In the same time period, Kerr also contributed to [[Yahoo!]] as an NBA commentator.\n\nHe has provided his voice for the in-game commentary of [[EA Sports]] [[video game]]s ''[[NBA Live series|NBA Live 06]], [[NBA Live series|NBA Live 07]], [[NBA Live series|NBA Live 08]], [[NBA Live series|NBA Live 09]]'' and ''[[NBA Live series|NBA Live 10]]'' with Albert. He has also provided his voice as a color analyst for ''[[NBA 2K12]]'', ''[[NBA 2K13]]'', ''[[NBA 2K14]]'' and ''[[NBA 2K15]]''. He remained a commentator in ''[[NBA 2K15]]'' despite becoming the [[Golden State Warriors]] coach for the 2014\u201315 season several months prior to the game's release.\n\nKerr left broadcasting in 2007 to become general manager for the [[Phoenix Suns]], but it was confirmed on June 28, 2010 that he would return as an NBA analyst for TNT starting with the [[2010\u201311 NBA season]]. Since 2011, Kerr has also called the [[NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Championship]] on Turner Sports and [[CBS]], teaming up with lead broadcasters [[Jim Nantz]] and [[Clark Kellogg]] for the First Four and Final Four games, and with Albert in other rounds.\n\nKerr was a regular contributor to the website ''[[Grantland]]'' from 2011 until it closed in 2015.\n\n==Executive career==\n\n===Phoenix Suns (2004\u20132010)===\nOn April 15, 2004, Kerr was announced as a member of a potential group of buyers that would acquire his old team, the Phoenix Suns, from [[Jerry Colangelo]] for $300 million. He became part of Suns management, acting as a consultant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/suns/news/kerr_bio.html|title=STEVE KERR BIO \u2013 THE OFFICIAL SITE OF THE PHOENIX SUNS|work=NBA.com|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/suns/news/directory.html|title=Latest Headlines|work=Phoenix Suns|access-date=}}</ref> During the [[2006 NBA All-Star Weekend]], he was a member of the San Antonio team that won the [[NBA All-Star Weekend Shooting Stars Competition|Shooting Stars Competition]].<ref>{{cite web|title=NBA All-Star Shooting Stars Winners|date=August 24, 2017|website=NBA.com|url=http://www.nba.com/history/all-star/shooting-stars#/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180224155543/http://www.nba.com/history/all-star/shooting-stars|archivedate=February 24, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn June 2, 2007, Kerr announced that he would become the [[general manager]] of the [[Phoenix Suns]] beginning with the 2007\u20132008 season. In 2008, the Suns traded forward [[Shawn Marion]] and guard [[Marcus Banks]] to the Miami Heat in exchange for [[Shaquille O'Neal]]. The Suns were eliminated by the [[San Antonio Spurs]] in five games in the first round of the playoffs. On December 10, 2008, Kerr continued to remake the Suns roster by trading [[Boris Diaw]], [[Raja Bell]], and [[Sean Singletary]] to the [[Charlotte Bobcats]] in exchange for [[Jason Richardson]], [[Jared Dudley]], and the Bobcats' 2010 second-round draft pick, which was used to draft [[Gani Lawal]] of [[Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets men's basketball|Georgia Tech]].<ref>{{cite news|date=December 10, 2008|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2008/basketball/nba/12/10/suns.bobcats.trade.ap/index.html?eref=si_topstories|title=Suns land Richardson from 'Cats|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081211204234/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2008/basketball/nba/12/10/suns.bobcats.trade.ap/index.html?eref=si_topstories |archivedate=December 11, 2008 }}</ref> On June 25, 2009, Kerr traded O'Neal to the Cleveland Cavaliers for [[Ben Wallace]], [[Aleksandar Pavlovi\u0107|Sasha Pavlovic]], a future second-round draft pick and cash.\n\nOn May 5, 2010, the Suns wore ''Los Suns'' jerseys in Game 2 against the [[San Antonio Spurs|Spurs]] to be united against the controversial [[Arizona SB 1070|Arizona immigration law]]. Kerr himself compared the law to [[Nazi Germany]].<ref>{{cite web | last=Coro | first=Paul | date=May 4, 2010 | url=http://www.azcentral.com/sports/suns/articles/2010/05/04/20100504phoenix-suns-los-suns-jerseys.html | publisher=[[The Arizona Republic]] | title=Phoenix to wear 'Los Suns' jerseys for Game 2 vs. Spurs | access-date=May 2, 2017 | quote=\"It's hard to imagine in this country that we have to produce papers,\" Kerr said. \"It brings up images of Nazi Germany. We understand that the intentions of the law are not for that to happen, but you have to be very, very careful. . . . It's important that everyone in our state and nation understands this is an issue that needs to be explored. So, we're trying to expose it.\"}}</ref>\n\nOn June 15, 2010, Kerr stepped down as president and general manager of the Suns. He continued to own a one percent share of the Suns' organization until 2014.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\n==Coaching career==\n\n===Golden State Warriors (2014\u2013present)===\n[[File:Steve Kerr Talks to Reporters.jpg|thumb|upright|250px|Kerr in 2017]]\nOn May 14, 2014, Kerr reached an agreement to become the head coach for the [[Golden State Warriors]], succeeding [[Mark Jackson (basketball)|Mark Jackson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/warriors/news/kerr-20140514|title=Warriors Reach Agreement in Principle for Steve Kerr to Become Team's Head Coach \u2013 THE OFFICIAL SITE OF THE GOLDEN STATE WARRIORS|work=nba.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/10933515/steve-kerr-accepts-golden-state-warriors-coaching-position|title=Steve Kerr accepts Golden State Warriors' coaching position|work=ESPN.com}}</ref> Kerr coached in the 2014 [[NBA Summer League|Summer League]] for the Warriors. During the [[2014\u201315 Golden State Warriors season|2014\u201315 season]], the team's offense employed elements of the [[triangle offense]] from his playing days in Chicago under [[Phil Jackson]], the spacing and pace of [[Gregg Popovich]] in San Antonio, and the uptempo principles [[Mike D'Antoni]] and later [[Alvin Gentry]] used in Phoenix when Kerr was the GM.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gonzalez|first=Antonio|title=Kerr coming to New York as an All-Star coach with Warriors|date=February 10, 2015|work=SFGate.com|agency=Associated Press|url=http://stats.sfgate.com/nba/story.asp?i=20150210031753362136008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150526052151/http://stats.sfgate.com/nba/story.asp?i=20150210031753362136008|archivedate=May 26, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Slater|first=Anthony|title=The Warriors and Rockets aren\u2019t as similar as you think \u2014 it\u2019s a fascinating strategic and stylistic matchup|date=May 10, 2018|work=The Athletic|url=https://theathletic.com/348148/2018/05/09/the-warriors-and-rockets-arent-as-similar-as-you-think-its-a-fascinating-strategic-and-stylistic-matchup-2/|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nAfter the Warriors beat the Houston Rockets to win their 14th consecutive game, Kerr became the first coach to start his career with a 19\u20132 record.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/nba/news/warriors-steve-kerr-record-stats-knicks-stephen-curry-klay-thompson-phil-jackson/dk0ehdhr145p18t0hgbgdg6en|title=Warriors' Steve Kerr off to best start in history for first-year coach|date=December 11, 2014|publisher=|accessdate=June 13, 2017}}</ref> This beat out Al Cervi and his 18\u20132 start with the Syracuse Nationals. On December 10, 2014, Kerr became the first NBA rookie head coach to win 21 of his first 23 games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20141210/HOUGSW/gameinfo.html?ls=slt|title=Rockets at Warriors|work=NBA.com}}</ref> He was named the head coach of the Western Conference team for the [[2015 NBA All-Star Game]] after Golden State had the best record in the conference.<ref>{{cite web|title=Steve Kerr to coach West All-Stars|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/12211278/steve-kerr-golden-state-warriors-coach-western-conference-all-stars|website=www.espn.com|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=February 16, 2015}}</ref> On April 4, the Warriors beat the Dallas Mavericks 123\u2013110 to clinch [[home advantage|home-court advantage]] throughout the playoffs, and Kerr got his 63rd win of the season to become the highest winning rookie head coach in NBA history, passing [[Tom Thibodeau]] and his 62 wins with the Chicago Bulls in the 2010\u201311 season. In the [[NBA Coach of the Year]] voting, Kerr was runner-up to [[Mike Budenholzer]].\n\nThe Warriors ultimately finished with one of the best regular seasons in NBA history, and the greatest in the team's 69-year history. Golden State ended with an overall record of 67\u201315, becoming the 10th team to win 67 or more games in a single season. It was the first time the Warriors had ever won as many as 60 games in a season; their previous high was 59 in the 1975\u201376 season. The Warriors also ended with a 39\u20132 home record, which is tied for the second best home record in NBA history. The Warriors were first in defensive efficiency for the season and second in offensive efficiency, barely missing the mark that the [[Julius Erving]]\u2013led Sixers achieved by being first in both offensive and defensive efficiency. They became the first team in NBA history to have two win streaks over 15 at home (18 and 19).\n\nIn the opening round of the playoffs against the [[New Orleans Pelicans]], Kerr led the Warriors to their first four-game playoff sweep since the [[1975 NBA Finals]]. Afterwards, the team surpassed the [[Memphis Grizzlies]] (4\u20132, in the second round). Down 2\u20131 in the series, Kerr made an unconventional adjustment in Game 4 to leave the Grizzlies' [[Tony Allen (basketball)|Tony Allen]] open and have his defender, center [[Andrew Bogut]], guard the interior. His strategy was lauded after Allen, Memphis' best wing defender, was benched and limited to 16 minutes after missing wide open shots.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kawakami|first=Tim|title=The playoff evolution of Steve Kerr, in real time, through the ups, downs, struggles and eventual triumph in this series|date=May 16, 2015|newspaper=San Jose Mercury News|url=http://blogs.mercurynews.com/kawakami/2015/05/16/the-playoff-evolution-of-steve-kerr-in-real-time-through-the-ups-downs-struggles-and-eventual-triumph-in-this-series/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518014157/http://blogs.mercurynews.com/kawakami/2015/05/16/the-playoff-evolution-of-steve-kerr-in-real-time-through-the-ups-downs-struggles-and-eventual-triumph-in-this-series/|archivedate=May 18, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Scott|first=Nate|title=The Warriors' crazy defensive adjustment won them Game 4|date=May 12, 2015|newspaper=USA Today|url=http://ftw.usatoday.com/2015/05/warriors-grizzlies-steve-kerr-tony-allen|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150514171407/http://ftw.usatoday.com/2015/05/warriors-grizzlies-steve-kerr-tony-allen|archivedate=May 14, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Jenkins|first=Bruce|title=Warriors seem to have ingredients for greatness|date=May 18, 2015|newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle|url=http://www.sfchronicle.com/sports/jenkins/article/Warriors-seem-to-have-ingredients-for-greatness-6271537.php|accessdate=May 28, 2015|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The Warriors then defeated the [[Houston Rockets]] (4\u20131, in the [[NBA Conference Finals|Western Conference Finals]]), making the [[NBA Finals]] for the first time in 40 years.\n\nThe Warriors faced the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]] in the Finals. Kerr and rival coach [[David Blatt]] were both in their first season as NBA head coaches, and this was the first time a pair of rookie head coaches faced each other in the [[NBA Finals]] since the NBA's first year of existence, in 1947 with [[Eddie Gottlieb]] of the [[Philadelphia Warriors]] and [[Harold Olsen]] of the [[Chicago Stags]] competing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://probasketballtalk.nbcsports.com/2015/06/03/steve-kerr-and-david-blatt-meet-again-this-time-as-rookie-coaches-in-the-nba-finals/|title=Steve Kerr and David Blatt meet again, this time as rookie coaches in the NBA Finals \u2013 ProBasketballTalk|work=nbcsports.com}}</ref> After the Warriors went down 2\u20131 to Cleveland, Kerr started [[swingman]] [[Andre Iguodala]] in place of Bogut, jump-starting their stagnant offense for a 103\u201382 road win that evened the series. It was Iguodala's first start of the season, and the small unit came to be known as the [[Death Lineup]]. After the game, Kerr admitted to lying to the press in response to pregame questions about potential changes to his starting lineup.<ref>{{cite news|last=Deveney|first=Steve|title=Steve Kerr lied, and the Warriors took advantage in Game 4|date=June 12, 2015|work=Sporting News|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/nba/story/2015-06-12/nba-finals-golden-state-warriors-steve-kerr-coach-starting-lineup-andre-iguodala-lebron-james-stephen-curry|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150615093420/http://www.sportingnews.com/nba/story/2015-06-12/nba-finals-golden-state-warriors-steve-kerr-coach-starting-lineup-andre-iguodala-lebron-james-stephen-curry|archivedate=June 15, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The Warriors went on to win the championship in six games, defeating the Cavaliers, 4\u20132, in the series, to give Kerr his sixth championship and first as a head coach.\n\nAfter the first two days of the defending champion Warriors' training camp, Kerr took an indefinite leave of absence to rehabilitate his back, which had caused problems since the [[2015 NBA Finals]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/warriors/news/kerr-leave-of-absence-20151001|title=Warriors Head Coach Steve Kerr to Take a Leave of Absence to Focus on Back Rehab|work=NBA.com|date=October 1, 2015|accessdate=October 1, 2015}}</ref> Around this time, assistant coach [[Luke Walton]] assumed Kerr's coaching duties. Kerr missed all of 2015 and most of January 2016, although technically the NBA credited Walton's win-loss record to Kerr.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/nba-news/4662300-luke-walton-coaching-record-wins-steve-kerr-warriors-coaching-record-stephen-curry|website=[[Sporting News]]|title=NBA reportedly considers crediting Luke Walton with Warriors' wins|accessdate=December 1, 2015}}</ref> Kerr said \"I think it's ridiculous\", when asked about getting all of Walton's wins.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/14210568/luke-walton-golden-state-warriors-winless-wonder|website=[[ESPN]]|title=Luke Walton, the Warriors' winless wonder}}</ref> On January 22, 2016, Kerr returned to coaching after missing 43 games, but warned he might need to miss games occasionally if there was a recurrence of the headaches and pain related to the [[spinal fluid leak]] that sidelined him. The Warriors went 39\u20134 with interim coach [[Luke Walton]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Shelburne|first=Ramona|title=Kerr battles lingering spinal-fluid issues, but coaches through pain|date=February 10, 2016|website=ESPN.com|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/14757415/steve-kerr-battles-headaches-lingering-spinal-fluid-issues-coaches-pain|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160214001914/http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/14757415/steve-kerr-battles-headaches-lingering-spinal-fluid-issues-coaches-pain|archivedate=February 14, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The Warriors went 34-5 after Kerr returned to coaching. Golden State broke the [[1995\u201396 Chicago Bulls season|1995\u201396 Chicago Bulls]] 72\u201310 record by winning 73 games.<ref name=\"usa today 73 wins\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nba/warriors/2016/04/14/warriors-get-73rd-win-set-nba-record/83018630/|title=Warriors notch NBA-record 73rd win to surpass 1995-96 Bulls|first=Sam|last=Amick|date=April 14, 2016|work=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=April 14, 2016}}</ref> Kerr became the first person in NBA history to be a part of 70-win teams as a player and head coach. He was named 2015\u201316 [[NBA Coach of the Year]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/2016/news/04/26/steve-kerr-named-nba-coach-of-the-year-2015-16/index.html|title=Warriors' Kerr named 2015-16 NBA Coach of the Year|date=April 26, 2016|publisher=NBA.com|accessdate=April 26, 2016}}</ref> Kerr would lead the Warriors to the [[2016 NBA Finals]] where they would again face the Cleveland Cavaliers. The Warriors lost in seven games.\n\n[[File:1 steve kerr 2019.jpg|thumb|Kerr at Game 2 of the [[2019 NBA Finals]]]]\nOn November 20, 2016, the NBA announced that Kerr had been fined $25,000 for public criticism of officiating during a radio interview with [[KNBR (AM)|KNBR]] 680 on November 17.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/18094259/golden-state-warriors-coach-steve-kerr-fined-25000-public-criticism-officiating|title=Kerr fined $25K for publicly criticizing officials|newspaper=ESPN.com|access-date=November 20, 2016}}</ref> Kerr missed time during the 2017 playoffs due to recurring back issues.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Boren|first1=Cindy|title=Steve Kerr had procedure to repair spinal cord leak, Warriors owner says|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/early-lead/wp/2017/05/07/steve-kerr-had-procedure-to-repair-spinal-cord-leak-warriors-owner-says/?noredirect=on|website=Washington Post|accessdate=May 10, 2018|date=May 7, 2017}}</ref> Associate head coach [[Mike Brown (basketball, born 1970)|Mike Brown]] has acted as acting head coach during periods of Kerr's absence, and Brown continued head coaching into the playoffs leading the Warriors to a 12\u20130 record in the postseason. Kerr returned for the [[2017 NBA Finals]] where he led the Warriors to victory over the Cleveland Cavaliers in five games. The Warriors finished the playoffs with a 16\u20131 record, the best postseason winning percentage in NBA history.<ref>{{cite web|title=Warriors (16-1) Record Best Postseason Winning Percentage in NBA History|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2715556-warriors-16-1-record-best-postseason-winning-percentage-in-nba-history|website=Bleacher Report|accessdate=May 10, 2018|date=June 14, 2017}}</ref> Kerr is the fourth coach in NBA history to win two championships in his first three seasons of coaching. Kerr won his third championship as a head coach when the Warriors defeated the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]] in the [[2018 NBA Finals]] in four games to give Kerr his eighth championship of his career.\n\nKerr is third on the Warriors' all-time wins list behind [[Don Nelson]] and [[Eddie Gottlieb]], and only Nelson has won more games in the West Coast portion of Warriors history.{{citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\nHe also became the first head coach in NBA History to have led his team towards 67 or more wins in three consecutive seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/coaches/kerrst01c.html|title=Steve Kerr Coaching Record|accessdate=July 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Political views==\nSince the conclusion of the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 U.S. presidential election]], Kerr has been critical of [[Donald Trump]] and his election victory. In an interview following the election, Kerr voiced the opinion that Trump's rise to power was based on insults against women and minorities. He compared Trump's campaign performances and the crude responses of his supporters to ''[[The Jerry Springer Show]]''. Although he expressed hope that Trump would be a good president, he made clear his \"disgust\" with Trump's disrespectful public discourse and his disappointment with the election results.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ftw.usatoday.com/2016/11/warriors-steve-kerr-trump-presidential-election-rant-america |title=Steve Kerr goes on pregame rant about presidential election: \u2018I thought we were better than this' |last=Tsuji |first=Alysha |date=November 9, 2016 |publisher=[[USA Today]] |access-date=August 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\nKerr has been a strong supporter of [[gun control]], expressing disappointment with the government\u2019s response to school shootings.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/early-lead/wp/2018/02/14/its-disgusting-steve-kerr-criticizes-governments-response-to-mass-shootings/ |title=\u2018Children are being shot to death day after day\u2019: Steve Kerr criticizes government\u2019s response |last=Johnson |first=Thomas |date=February 15, 2018 |publisher=[[Washington Post]] |access-date=August 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nKerr married Margot Kerr, his college sweetheart, in 1990. They have three children: Nick, Maddy and Matthew.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playerwives.com/nba/golden-state-warriors/steve-kerrs-wife-margot-kerr/|title=Steve Kerr's wife Margot Kerr - PlayerWives.com|date=May 15, 2014|publisher=|accessdate=June 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{NBA player statistics legend|champion=y|leader=y|record=y}}\n\n===NBA===\n\n====Regular season====\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|1988}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1988\u201389 Phoenix Suns season|Phoenix]]\n| 26 || 0 || 6.0 || .435 || .471 || .667|| .7 || .9 || .3 || .0 || 2.1\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|1989}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1989\u201390 Cleveland Cavaliers season|Cleveland]]\n| 78 || 5 || 21.3 || .444 ||bgcolor=\"CFECEC\"| .507* || .863 || 1.3 || '''3.2''' || .6 || .1 || 6.7\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|1990}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1990\u201391 Cleveland Cavaliers season|Cleveland]]\n| 57 || 4 || 15.9 || .444 || .452 || .849 || .6 || 2.3 || .5 || .1 || 4.8\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|1991}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1991\u201392 Cleveland Cavaliers season|Cleveland]]\n| 48 || '''20''' || 17.6 || .511 || .432 || .833 || '''1.6''' || 2.3 || .6 || '''.2''' || 6.6\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|1992}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1992\u201393 Cleveland Cavaliers season|Cleveland]]\n| 5 || 0 || 8.2 || .500 || .000 || '''1.000''' || 1.4 || 2.2 || .4 || .0 || 2.4\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|1992}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1992\u201393 Orlando Magic season|Orlando]]\n| 47 || 0 || 9.4 || .429 || .250 || .909 || .8 || 1.3 || .2 || .0 || 2.6 \n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|1993}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1